<subSubSection id="675FED7F7B755B9E15E07263DE361267" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" type="color in alcohol">
<paragraph id="2B0AD4E2CAB562EF6FAC1ABAAC931B13" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Color in alcohol.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="40B94964E7B2C84DE9CBF18B46CF173C" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Light tan overall, with no visible markings.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63A5AC1236AF48950CEEBA2B31C38A7E" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E053CF6346C737662FDF31756C683FEE" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="50E0A4BB1562BC5A619A07054193EFBD" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<taxonomicName id="17106D5F4EEFF35713CAC8BC217A5861" authorityName="Shepherd &amp; Phelps &amp; Pinheiro &amp; Rocha &amp; Rocha" authorityYear="2020" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectranthias polygonius" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="polygonius">
<emphasis id="59276414B9C113C485F4B917B3437C0C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Plectranthias polygonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is named for the orange rhomboid-shaped polygons arranged in parallel rows along the lateral midline that distinguish it from all other known species within the genus. To be treated as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="16C607DF5B38246BE7159E090FF21E4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7724F3AAE37873E102DF68EE42D1D808" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C3ECEA25CF35D187028DA631B3E9326C" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<taxonomicName id="EAA6524B7ADDF773B029DDF790E7F507" authorityName="Shepherd &amp; Phelps &amp; Pinheiro &amp; Rocha &amp; Rocha" authorityYear="2020" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectranthias polygonius" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="polygonius">
<emphasis id="646DB00572B33C0D96E4ECDBE1CEC945" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Plectranthias polygonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. appears to be the same species as an undescribed 
<taxonomicName id="CF4D77A834C06A36CBF3A234281FA544" authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1873" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectranthias" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ECD2717AC059A9CF6054882692642B29" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Plectranthias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species that was photographed off Rangiroa, French Polynesia, at a depth of 65 m (
<bibRefCitation id="B6BABBCBEFD0213FB70154C24C8A1179" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3647.1.8" author="Williams, JT" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="167 - 180" refId="B25" refString="Williams, JT, Delrieu-Trottin, E, Planes, S, 2013. Two new fish species of the subfamily Anthiinae (Perciformes, Serranidae) from the Marquesas. Zootaxa 3647 (1): 167 - 180, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3647.1.8" title="Two new fish species of the subfamily Anthiinae (Perciformes, Serranidae) from the Marquesas." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3647.1.8" volume="3647" year="2013">Williams et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). However, some superficial differences exist between our specimen and the one in 
<bibRefCitation id="08E56F613B2CF62DB566FD67C7612A98" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3647.1.8" author="Williams, JT" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="167 - 180" refId="B25" refString="Williams, JT, Delrieu-Trottin, E, Planes, S, 2013. Two new fish species of the subfamily Anthiinae (Perciformes, Serranidae) from the Marquesas. Zootaxa 3647 (1): 167 - 180, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3647.1.8" title="Two new fish species of the subfamily Anthiinae (Perciformes, Serranidae) from the Marquesas." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3647.1.8" volume="3647" year="2013">Williams et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, including the thickness of the white lines on the upper body and the color of the iris. These may be due to individual variability. The two specimens described in this paper were collected in highly complex reefs predominantly covered by coralline algae and sponges in Tahiti (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8000C99AA39AF9838EE6AC789280A484" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Habitat of Plectranthias polygonius sp. nov. and Plectranthias hinano sp. nov. in A Tahiti, French Polynesia, depth of approximately 100 m, and B Erikub Atoll, Republic of the Marshall Islands, depth of approximately 120 m. Photographs by LA Rocha." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.941.50243.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/421776" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">3A</figureCitation>
) and crevices of steep reef walls in the Marshall Islands (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="35AE1E910FD279CD1C7AC66701A762DA" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Habitat of Plectranthias polygonius sp. nov. and Plectranthias hinano sp. nov. in A Tahiti, French Polynesia, depth of approximately 100 m, and B Erikub Atoll, Republic of the Marshall Islands, depth of approximately 120 m. Photographs by LA Rocha." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.941.50243.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/421776" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">3B</figureCitation>
), indicating that this species probably has a wider Pacific distribution. All known individuals have been observed or collected at mesophotic depths, suggesting that 
<taxonomicName id="97434EF69B93150B24B8B6E150D4068F" authorityName="Shepherd &amp; Phelps &amp; Pinheiro &amp; Rocha &amp; Rocha" authorityYear="2020" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectranthias polygonius" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="polygonius">
<emphasis id="15BA91CAB1E7865436665627E9661358" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Plectranthias polygonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., as with most of its congeners, does not inhabit shallow coral reef habitats.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF53E7D0E382AE7A55B9617FED71472C" doi="10.3897/zookeys.941.50243.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/421776" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="77C1B7E50960D607859E53C38B702B62" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis id="BD105256DF64F1426310EE9FBBCCADF9" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Figure 3.</emphasis>
Habitat of 
<taxonomicName id="BE23518F0C4B736B3D09DC95C36F9A7B" authorityName="Shepherd &amp; Phelps &amp; Pinheiro &amp; Rocha &amp; Rocha" authorityYear="2020" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectranthias polygonius" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="polygonius">
<emphasis id="140BBD4230A66CB3828C5784D8970DA8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Plectranthias polygonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName id="AED8D92E65768C8AFDCDE514E9E0766A" authorityName="Shepherd &amp; Phelps &amp; Pinheiro &amp; Rocha &amp; Rocha" authorityYear="2020" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectranthias hinano" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hinano">
<emphasis id="E01F7DD30C2E588D03F8F50A9B319366" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Plectranthias hinano</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. in 
<emphasis id="DDFD0BF838A986A050D229E4648F73E1" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">A</emphasis>
Tahiti, French Polynesia, depth of approximately 100 m, and 
<emphasis id="463F6F20C44D9638D63CC4547271D0CD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">B</emphasis>
Erikub Atoll, Republic of the Marshall Islands, depth of approximately 120 m. Photographs by LA Rocha.
</paragraph>
